<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-06-20T23:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-06-20T23:36:00-05:00" n="1235" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1235">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/4258.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-20T22:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 20, 1912—10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I left a memorandum with the President this evening similar to my note to
                            the Minister. The President explicitly said that no bullets would be
                            allowed to penetrate American territory, and that if artillery is
                            employed steps will be taken to prevent injury to Americans. He said a
                            siege might be employed if the city is closed on the American side. The
                            President, however, stated that no troops were advancing on or near
                            Ciudad Juárez. Note the disagreement between the President’s and the
                            Minister’s remarks.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>